  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the US\n- Initial focus on reporting large financial transactions\n- Limited regulatory framework\n\n2. International Development\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Created international standards for anti-money laundering (AML)\n- Developed recommendations for global financial institutions\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Expanded reporting and monitoring obligations\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Modern Regulatory Approaches\n- Enhanced Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Risk-based assessment frameworks\n- Mandatory beneficial ownership disclosures\n- Cryptocurrency transaction monitoring\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Stricter cross-border information sharing\n- Advanced technology for transaction tracking\n- Increased focus on digital currency regulations\n- Comprehensive corporate transparency requirements\n\n6. Global Coordination\n- Synchronized international AML standards\n- Collaborative enforcement mechanisms\n- Multilateral information exchange platforms\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, adapting to emerging financial technologies and sophisticated laundering techniques.",
